The sample mean \(\bar{X}\) of a random sample of size \(n = 12\) from a uniform distribution on \((0,1)\) has a mean \(\mu = 0.5\) and variance \(\sigma^2 / n = (1/12) / 12 = 1/144\), so the standard deviation is \(1/12\).

Using the Central Limit Theorem, \(\bar{X}\) is approximately normally distributed. The probability \(P(0.5 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3)\) is approximated by standardizing to the standard normal distribution. The standardized variable is \(Z = (\bar{X} - 0.5) / (1/12) = 12(\bar{X} - 0.5)\).

- At \(\bar{X} = 0.5\), \(Z = 12(0.5 - 0.5) = 0\).  
- At \(\bar{X} = 2/3\), \(Z = 12(2/3 - 0.5) = 12(1/6) = 2\).  

Thus, \(P(0.5 \leq \bar{X} \leq 2/3) = P(0 \leq Z \leq 2)\), where \(Z\) is standard normal.  
This is \(\Phi(2) - \Phi(0)\), with \(\Phi(0) = 0.5\) and \(\Phi(2) \approx 0.9772\).  
Therefore, \(P(0 \leq Z \leq 2) \approx 0.9772 - 0.5 = 0.4772\).  

Rounded to three significant figures, the probability is 0.477.  

