* RESPONSE 1 *
**************
The probability of visiting a physical therapist is denoted as \(P(A)\), and the probability of visiting a chiropractor is \(P(C)\). Given that 28% visit both, \(P(A \text{ and } C) = 0.28\). Also, 8% visit neither, so \(P(\text{neither}) = 0.08\). The probability of visiting a physical therapist exceeds that of visiting a chiropractor by 16 percentage points, so \(P(A) = P(C) + 0.16\).

The probability of visiting at least one is \(P(A \text{ or } C) = 1 - P(\text{neither}) = 1 - 0.08 = 0.92\). Using the inclusion-exclusion principle:  
\[P(A \text{ or } C) = P(A) + P(C) - P(A \text{ and } C)\]  
\[0.92 = P(A) + P(C) - 0.28\]  
\[P(A) + P(C) = 0.92 + 0.28 = 1.20\]

Substituting \(P(A) = P(C) + 0.16\):  
\[(P(C) + 0.16) + P(C) = 1.20\]  
\[2P(C) + 0.16 = 1.20\]  
\[2P(C) = 1.20 - 0.16 = 1.04\]  
\[P(C) = 1.04 / 2 = 0.52\]

Then,  
\[P(A) = 0.52 + 0.16 = 0.68\]

