- \(D_0(\mathrm{H}_2^{+}) = 2.651 \, \mathrm{eV}\)
- \(\text{IE}_{\mathrm{H}} = 13.598 \, \mathrm{eV}\) (standard value for atomic hydrogen ionization energy)

Substitute the values:
\[
\text{IE}_{\mathrm{H}_2} = 4.478 + 13.598 - 2.651
\]

First, add \(4.478\) and \(13.598\):
\[
4.478 + 13.598 = 18.076
\]

Then, subtract \(2.651\):
\[
18.076 - 2.651 = 15.425
\]

The result is \(15.425 \, \mathrm{eV}\). Considering significant figures, the input values \(4.478\) and \(2.651\) have four significant figures, and \(13.598\) has five. The calculated value \(15.425\) is rounded to four significant figures, resulting in \(15.43 \, \mathrm{eV}\).

