Solution: The energy of one mole of photons with a wavelength of 300 nm is calculated using the formula \(E = \frac{N_A h c}{\lambda}\), where \(N_A\) is Avogadro's number (\(6.022 \times 10^{23} \, \text{mol}^{-1}\)), \(h\) is Planck's constant (\(6.626 \times 10^{-34} \, \text{J·s}\)), \(c\) is the speed of light (\(2.998 \times 10^8 \, \text{m/s}\)), and \(\lambda\) is the wavelength in meters (\(300 \, \text{nm} = 3.00 \times 10^{-7} \, \text{m}\)).

First, compute the energy in joules per mole:  
\[
E = \frac{(6.022 \times 10^{23}) \times (6.626 \times 10^{-34}) \times (2.998 \times 10^8)}{3.00 \times 10^{-7}} = 398.9 \, \text{kJ/mol} \quad (\text{after converting to kJ/mol by dividing by } 1000).
\]

The wavelength is given with three significant figures (300 nm), so the result is rounded to three significant figures, yielding 399 kJ/mol.

