Problem: Calculate the magnitude of the spin angular momentum of a proton. Give a numerical answer.  The unit of the answer should be  $10^{-35} \mathrm{~J} \mathrm{~s}$.
Solution: The magnitude of the spin angular momentum of a proton is given by the formula \( S = \sqrt{s(s+1)}  \hbar \), where \( s = \frac{1}{2} \) is the spin quantum number for a proton. Substituting the value, \( S = \sqrt{\frac{1}{2} \times \frac{3}{2}}  \hbar = \sqrt{\frac{3}{4}}  \hbar = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}  \hbar \).

Using the reduced Planck's constant \( \hbar \approx 1.0545718 \times 10^{-34}  \text{J·s} \) and \( \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2} \approx 0.8660254 \), the calculation is:
\[
S = 0.8660254 \times 1.0545718 \times 10^{-34} \approx 9.13286 \times 10^{-35}  \text{J·s}.
\]

Rounded to three significant figures, \( S \approx 9.13 \times 10^{-35}  \text{J·s} \). In the unit of \( 10^{-35}  \text{J·s} \), the numerical value is 9.13.

